        "heading": "H1: 10 Most Common Smart Contract Vulnerabilities — With Code Examples",
        "content": "URL:*Schema:***Internal Links:*\n**1. Reentrancy*Prevention: OpenZeppelin ReentrancyGuard. CEI (Checks-Effects-Interactions) pattern.\n\n**2. Integer Overflow/Underflow*Prevention: Use Solidity 0.8+. Avoid `unchecked` for user-controlled values.\n\n**3. Access Control (Missing Modifier)*Prevention: OpenZeppelin Ownable, AccessControl. Every privileged function needs a modifier.\n\n**4. Oracle Manipulation*Prevention: TWAP oracles, Chainlink + TWAP dual-oracle.\n\n**5. Flash Loan Attacks*Prevention: Require multi-block consistency for price-sensitive operations. Flash loan-proof design.\n\n**6. Unchecked External Call Returns*If the call fails silently, the state has already been updated.\nPrevention: Always check return value: `(bool success,) = addr.call{...}(...); require(success);`\n\n**7. Delegatecall to Untrusted Contract*Prevention: Strict access control on upgradeability. Never delegatecall to user-supplied addresses.\n\n**8. Griefing (Gas Limit DoS)*Prevention: Limit array growth. Use pagination for large iterations. Pull-over-push pattern.\n\n**9. Front-Running*Prevention: Commit-reveal scheme. Flashbots bundles. Slippage limits. Private mempool.\n\n**10. Price Impact Manipulation (ERC-777 / Callback Issues)*Prevention: Use ERC-20 only in DeFi. Treat any external call as a potential reentrancy vector.\n\n[BUTTON — PRIMARY] Book a Free Strategy Call →"
